post_text: Reminder: Join us from 5:30-7 pm on Friday, July 10 and provide input and feedback on a draft Return to School framework. In advance of Town hall, the draft framework will be available on Thursday, July 9 for public review at https://www.wccusd.net/return2school. A 32-member task force of students, families, teachers, administrators and District staff has been developing the frameworks based on surveys, focus groups and information gathered from Contra Costa County Health Services, Contra Costa County Office of Education and the California Department of Education. Please share widely with your friends and family to ensure that we have a wide representation of the WCCUSD community. Our plan is due July 20 to CCCOE. The meeting is via Zoom https://zoom.us/j/94137692306 or by phone 669-900-6833, ID: 941 3769 2306

Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed. Learn more at https://ca.p-ebt.org/

Debido al Coronavirus (COVID-19), los niños que son elegibles para recibir comidas gratuitas o a precio reducido en la escuela obtendrán beneficios adicionales de alimentos. Los beneficios EBT o P-EBT que se proporcionan debido a la pandemia, ayudan a las familias en California a comprar alimentos cuando las escuelas están cerradas. Obtenga más información en https://ca.p-ebt.org/.

post_text: Today is #NationalTeacherAppreciationDay. In honor of the day, we highlight the Ed Fund's #TeachingExcellence recipients. This year's honorees are Chavez Elementary Third Grade Teacher Cesar Dante-Barragan (bottom right), Lupine Hills Elementary Transitional Kindergarten Teacher Crystal Turner (top right), Lincoln Elementary School Third Grade Teacher Jesus Alfredo Galindo (top left) and Korematsu Middle School English Teacher Sydney Schantz (bottom left). We will post stories of the four recipients throughout the day. Congratulations to the quartet. And thank you to all WCCUSD teachers and educators for all that you do. text: Today is #NationalTeacherAppreciationDay. In honor of the day, we highlight the Ed Fund's #TeachingExcellence recipients. This year's honorees are Chavez Elementary Third Grade Teacher Cesar Dante-Barragan (bottom right), Lupine Hills Elementary Transitional Kindergarten Teacher Crystal Turner (top right), Lincoln Elementary School Third Grade Teacher Jesus Alfredo Galindo (top left) and Korematsu Middle School English Teacher Sydney Schantz (bottom left). We will post stories of the four recipients throughout the day. Congratulations to the quartet. And thank you to all WCCUSD teachers and educators for all that you do. United Teachers of Richmond, CTA, NEA #LearningEveryDay #WholeChildWholeCommunity #TeacherAppreciationWeek

post_text:
Special Delivery: César Chavez Elementary School teacher Ms. Bedwell spent Friday, April 24 connecting with her fourth graders in a unique way. Ms. Bedwell drove to each one of her students' homes and delivered "Keep Learning, Thinking About You" bags. The bags were filled with art and school supplies and snacks. Here is Ms. Bedwell in her own words: "It was amazing! (My students) were so happy to see me, and loved their bags. My sweaty mask was worth it. I received a $1,000 grant which was doubled. I bought books, art supplies, games, snacks and flash cards. I am exhausted but I got some new energy and purpose back. I got enough to do one more run in the middle of May. I was just feeling pumped and wanted to share." The grant was provided by @ChevronRichmond and @DonorsChoose as part of the #KeepKidsLearning initiative.
Shout to Principal Evert and her team for sharing this wonderful story. #LearningEveryDay #WholeChildWholeCommunity #WeAreWCCUSD #TeachersRock

post_text: Family leaders from the African American School Advisory Team (AASAT), District Local Control and Accountability Plan (DLCAPS), Multilingual District Advisory Committee (MDAC), and the Special Education Community Advisory Committee (CAC) kicking off the first Families Rising Together Summit at Lovonya Dejean Middle to discuss ways to unite families around WCCUSD students. Topics covered include Family Engagement, Budget Reductions, and Shared Recommendations. Ed Fund Executive Director Jasmine Jones, an El Cerrito High graduate, started off the event with a keynote address about working together. The event continues until 2 pm. #LearningEveryDay #WholeChildWholeCommunity

post_text:
Due to PG&E’s power outage, Pinole Valley High School will be closed on Monday. The other schools without power: Ellerhorst, Kensington, Madera, and Stewart schools will be open. Pinole Valley is closed due to logistics of serving that number of students without power.

Ellerhorst, Kensington, Madera and Stewart schools will have extra personnel in place to ensure a safe and productive school day.

We are continuing to monitor the situation, including the weather and wind forecasts and we will continue to provide you updates as we receive them.

Please stay safe and keep checking the District’s website www.wccusd.net and social media channels where we will be updating the situation.

PG&E informed us this morning that power at Pinole Valley High School, and Ellerhorst, Kensington, Madera, and Olinda elementary schools may be shut off at any time.

Schools will remain open for today on a normal Wednesday schedule and lunch will be served. Families/parents are more than welcome to pick up their children early if they choose. All after school programs and extracurricular activities at these five schools are cancelled for the day.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact your child’s school.

shared_text:
Paul Fadelli is with Matt Fadelli and 22 others.
October 3, 2019 at 4:24 AM ·

Thoughts are with my brother FRANK FADELLI who just had a major pancreatic cancer operation at Kaiser Oakland yesterday.

39 years in the Richmond/West Contra Costa Unified School District (WCCUSD) as a teacher, coach, dean and vice-principal at Harry Ells, Richmond, and Pinole Valley High schools, and Portola and Pinole Valley Middle schools.

Hang in there Frankie Jr.! Emily you've been amazing..

ICYMI: The Helms Middle School community held its grand opening ceremony for its Internationals Academy on Friday, Sept. 27. The Internationals Academy is part of the Internationals Network for Public Schools, which is designed to serve recently arrived immigrant and refugee English Learners (ELs) and ensure they reach high levels of academic achievement while also working towards fulfilling the requirements for college and beyond. It's the second academy to open in the District, following #RichmondHighSchool. #LearningEveryDay #WholeChildWholeCommunity

post_text: Thanks to our community partners at WestCAT, WCCUSD students in the Transition/Foster Youth program received several school supplies last week to help kick off a great school year. Wccusd Food Services Department
June 25, 2019 at 7:31 PM ·

Did you know children under the age of 18 can eat a free breakfast, lunch, and snack at one of 60 locations in West Contra Costa County throughout the summer? The West Contra Costa Unified School District Food Services program will serve meals as part of the Seamless Summer Feeding Program, sponsored by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, through Wednesday, August 14. Visit www.wccusd.net/summermeals for a list of locations and menus.

post_text: Meet 2019 #RichmondHighSchool graduates Jason Varela and Bruno De Leon. Jason and Bruno were two of 362 seniors that graduated during the Oilers’ 111th Commencement Ceremony on June 6. Bruno is on his way to San Francisco State University to study Business Administration, while Jason is headed to UCLA to study Psychobiology. Congratulations graduates. #LearningEveryDay #WholeChildWholeCommunity

post_text: El Cerrito High School Salutatorian Abigail Cain is off to @UCDavis to study Environmental Science.
